10
00:01:06,290 --> 00:01:12,140
So - knowing the actual outcome shouldn’t affect these estimates - but it does! This

11
00:01:12,140 --> 00:01:18,000
is known as the hindsight bias – or the “knew it all along” effect.

12
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:24,840
This effect was first empirically demonstrated by a classic 1975 article by Baruch Fischhoff

13
00:01:24,840 --> 00:01:30,140
of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, in which he asked the participants to estimate

14
00:01:30,140 --> 00:01:36,450
the likelihood of various outcomes to unfamiliar historical events.

15
00:01:36,450 --> 00:01:42,500
He found that not only did knowing the actual outcome increase people’s beliefs about

16
00:01:42,500 --> 00:01:48,950
the inevitability of that outcome, but people were largely unaware that their judgements

17
00:01:48,950 --> 00:01:52,130
were being affected.

18
00:01:52,130 --> 00:01:56,190
This bias has major implications for all sorts of things

19
00:01:56,400 --> 00:01:59,100
 – including the criminal justice system.

20
00:01:59,110 --> 00:02:03,560
To give just one example, in situations where we’re trying to judge whether someone has

21
